\begin_layout Title
Metricity and the Circle Map
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Linas Vepstas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
18 November 2023
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Kolomogorov's(?) circle map 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n+1}=x_{n}+\omega-K\sin2\pi x_{n}$
\end_inset

 famously exhibits both stable mode-locking behavior and chaotic motion.
 In the mode-locked regions, that is, when two different frequencies and
 couplings 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\omega,K\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\omega^{\prime},K^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

 are close enough to one-another, then the two different sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\left(\omega,K\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}\left(\omega^{\prime},K^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

 are generally close to one-another as well.
 This no longer holds when 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\omega,K\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\omega^{\prime},K^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

 are on opposite sides of a mode-locking boundary.
 This paper explores some of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{p}$
\end_inset

 metrics on the sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{n}-y_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 generated by the circle map.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The circle map 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n+1}=x_{n}+\omega-K\sin2\pi x_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a simplified model for weakly coupled oscillators and is broadly studied
 as a dynamical system having both periodic and chaotic behavior.
 It is intersting both mathematically, and from a physics and engineering
 point of view: it is a model of both electronic phase-locked loops, and
 for celestial mechanics, where tide-locking can force planetary bodies
 and moons to orbit in synchrony.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A prominent feature of the circle map is that, for many regions of the parameter
 space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\omega,K\right)$
\end_inset

 the map exhibits 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mode locking
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 behavior.
 That is, the iterated sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 rapidly settles down to a periodic orbit that is very stable against small
 perturbations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\omega,K\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The mode-locked regions are called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Arnold tongues
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; these are explicitly visible in the image below.
 Each such tongue has a vee shape, with the sharp tip located at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\omega_{0},K=0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In the mode-locked regions, the period of the orbit is given by the numerator
 of the Farey fraction that is nearest to the vee-tip frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

