\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The winding number property of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 means that the sequence is perenially increasing, and never returns to
 the same value twice.
 Yet, periodicity is forced by the perturbation term 
\begin_inset Formula $K\sin2\pi x_{n}$
\end_inset

, which remaps each 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 to the unit interval.
 This sequence, call it 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the associated reduced sequence
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}=x_{n}-\left\lfloor x_{n}\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

, is recurrent.
 (Think 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

u
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unit
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.) It is typically recurent in one of two ways: either the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ u_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 will settle down to asymptotically periodic orbits as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

, or it will not, chaoticaly visiting most or all of the unit interval.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
