\begin_layout Standard
The issue of the Laplacian changing signs, depending on which side of an
 edge one is sitting on, can be avoided by taking the absolute value, before
 summming.
 This replaces the Laplacian by a kind of direction-averaged gradient.
 This is direction-averaged absolute gradient is defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta x_{n}\left(\omega,K\right)=\frac{1}{M}\sum_{m=0}^{M}\left|x_{n}\left(\omega,K\right)-x_{n}\left(\omega+\delta\eta\cos\left(\frac{2\pi m}{M}\right),K+\delta\eta\sin\left(\frac{2\pi m}{M}\right)\right)\right|
\]

\end_inset

The five-point formula is obtained when 
\begin_inset Formula $M=4$
\end_inset

, so that the sine and cosine just sample to the left, right, above and
 below (of course, the Laplacian avoids the absolute value in the above.)
 The absolute value above allows 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x_{n}$
\end_inset

 to be understood as a first derivative, instead of a second derivative.
 The infinitessimal form of this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

direction-averaged absolute gradient
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 should be understood just the radial derivative; that is, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f\mapsto\left|\partial f/\partial\eta\right|$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\sqrt{\omega^{2}+K^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 I'm being sloppy, here.
 Whatever.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As long was we are being creative, note that other forms of averaging are
 possible: so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta_{p}f\left(\omega,K\right)=\left(\frac{1}{M}\sum_{m=0}^{M}\left|f\left(\omega,K\right)-f\left(\omega+\delta\eta\cos\left(\frac{2\pi m}{M}\right),K+\delta\eta\sin\left(\frac{2\pi m}{M}\right)\right)\right|^{p}\right)^{1/p}
\]

\end_inset

whose infinitessimal form should correspond to something similar to 
